h small, rural communities negotiated and experienced their religious lives. In exploring rural Dutch Reformed congregations, the book examines the complicated relationships between theology and practice and ‘lay’ and ‘elite’ religion and highlights challenges rural churches faced. As they faced these issues, Dieleman demonstrates that local congregations exercised agency within their lived religious experiences as they sought unique ways to navigate their own Reformed identity within their small, rural communities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aReformed ChurchzNetherlandsxHistoryy16th century. 0aRural churcheszNetherlandsxHistoryy16th century. 4aDutch and The Netherlands. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aReligion and Theology. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 16th Century.2bisacsh  aLow Countries, Reformation, Piety, Identity, Consistories.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311102374840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048550777?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048550777423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048550777/original  a978-3-11-102374-8  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles